  "verdict": "NEGATIVE. First-order overlap z=3668 is artifact of weak null (random integers vs concentrated small-odd knot dets). Mod-2 shows fundamental structural divergence: knot dets are ALL odd, lattice dets are 97.6% even (BC=0.15). For mod 3+, distributions converge toward uniform with no significant divergence. Cross-domain second-order (mod-3&5 conditioning on mod-7) shows no enrichment (z=-0.49). Within-domain second-order shows no structure. Multi-prime scan mean enrichment 1.02x +/- 0.05, consistent with noise.",
  "summary": "Knot and lattice determinant overlap is tested at first order (exact value sharing), mod-p distribution level (Bhattacharyya coefficient), within-domain second order (do shared-residue pairs have more similar auxiliary invariants?), and cross-domain second order (conditioning on mod-3 and mod-5, is mod-7 co-occurrence elevated?). The dominant signal is the mod-2 parity divergence: knot determinants are always odd (a theorem), while lattice determinants are overwhelmingly even. Beyond this known number-theoretic fact, no cross-domain resonance is detected.",
  "calibration_notes": {
    "first_order_z_inflated": "The z=3668 is meaningless: null draws uniform random integers from [1, max_det] which is astronomically sparse compared to the concentrated small-value knot dets. A proper null would condition on marginal distributions.",
    "mod2_is_theorem": "Knot determinants are always odd (they equal |Delta(-1)| for the Alexander polynomial, evaluated at -1). Lattice determinants being mostly even reflects that most lattice Gram matrices have even diagonal entries. This is number theory, not cross-domain resonance.",
    "expected_enrichment_not_found": "The hypothesized 1.2-1.6x enrichment is not present. Multi-prime scan shows 1.02x mean, well within noise."
  }
